state with index-0 (minimum). WORS was suggested as a possible stationary state based on the Onsager model in Ref. [50] and the LdG model in Ref. [51].
One can show that WORS remains a stationary point for all Œ± [49], but the Morse index of WORS changes [46]. Numerically, by using WORS at a smaller Œ± as an initial guess, we can always obtain WORS at a larger Œ±. Table I summarizes the Morse index of WORS as a saddle point at different Œ±. Physically, as Œ± increases, the larger confining area accommodates the development of other more complicated defect states. The parent WORS is no longer a stable state and the system begins to descend to other stable states.
Using our k-HiOSD method, we can exhaustively enumerate all possible states starting from WORS. Figure 2 presents the pathway maps for a number of

typical Œ±, where the defect states specified in the nodes are illustrated on the right panel. Take Fig. 2(c), for example. At Œ± ¬º 15, WORS is an index-2 saddle, which bifurcates to two boundary distortion (BD) states (related by œÄ=2 coordinate rotation) that are index-1 saddles. Both BD
states then further relax to two diagonal (D) states (again related by œÄ=2 coordinate rotation) as the global minima. This can be compared to the pathway map in 2(b) when Œ± ¬º 7, where the index-1 WORS is the direct pattern from

